rty who supported [[Robert Borden]]'s coalition government.\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 11 (1917)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 5% (1917)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 4 (1919)\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Parti canadien (1942)|Parti canadien]]\n|1942||????\n|anti-conscription\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1 (1942)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| {{sort|0.5|<1% (1942)}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|'' [[Qu\u00e9bec debout|Qu\u00e9bec debout/Groupe parliamentaire qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]]''\n|2018||{{dts|2018}}\n|Formed when several MPs left the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] due to the leadership of [[Martine Ouellet]]. Rejoined after she lost a leadership review vote and resigned.\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 7 (2018)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2% (2018)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}}\n| ''[[Senate Liberal Caucus]]'' <br /><small>{{lang|fr|Caucus lib\u00e9ral du S\u00e9nat}}</small>\n| 2014\n| 2019\n| [[Liberalism in Canada|Liberalism]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 32 (2014)\n|}\n\n=== Historical designations used by single candidates ===\n* Nationalist Liberal (Fleming Blanchard McCurdy), 1920 \u2014 McCurdy won a by-election under the Nationalist Liberal designation, but sat with the [[National Liberal and Conservative Party]] caucus\n* Protectionist (Joseph-\u00c9douard Moranville), 1926\n* Franc Lib (I) (Alfred Edward Watts), 1930\n* [[Prohibition Party (Canada)|Prohibition Party]] (Edwin Clarke Appleby), 1930\n* ''[[National Unity Party (Canada)|Parti national social chr\u00e9tien]]'' (Robert Rae Manville), 1934-1940\n* Anti-Communist (I) (Jean Tissot), 1935\n* [[Verdun (candidate)|Verdun]] (Herv\u00e9 Ferland), 1935\n* Veterans Party (Alloys Reginald Sprenger), 1935\n* Technocrat (Joseph McCrae Newman), 1935\n* Anti-Conscriptionist ([[Louis-G\u00e9rard Gosselin]]), 1940\n* [[Social Credit-National Unity]] (Harry Watson Arnold), 1940\n* [[National-Unity (candidate)|National-Unity]] (Robert Rae Manville), 1940\n* Trades Union (Nigel Morgan), 1945\n* [[Autonomist candidate]] (Paul Mass\u00e9), 1947\n* Christian Liberal (Howard A. Prentice), 1953\n* ''Locataire'' ([[Louis Seigneur]]), 1953\n* Anti-Communist (II) (Patrick Walsh), 1953\n* [[Canadian Democrat]] (Gerry Goeujon), 1957\n* [[National Credit Control]] (John Bernard Ball), 1957\n* ''Capital familial'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1957-1962\n* Liberal Conservative Coalition (George Rolland), 1957\n* ''[[Parti ouvrier canadien]]'' (Jean-Jacques Rouleau), 1958\n* [[League for Socialist Action]], 1961-1977\n* [[Co-operative Builders of Canada]] (Edgar-Bernard Charron), 1962\n*[[All Canadian Party]] (John Darby Naismith), 1962-1962\n* ''Parti humain familial'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1964\n* ''Droit vital personnel'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1965\n* [[Progressive Workers Movement]] (Jerry Le Bourdais), 1965\n* ''Esprit Social'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1967\u20131971\n* [[Work Less Party]] ([[Betty Krawczyk]]), 2007\u20132010\n* Franc Lib (II) (Jean-Roger Marcotte), 1968\n* [[Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency]] (formerly Online Party) (Michael Nicula), 2012\u20132016<ref name=\"Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency Deregistered\">{{cite web|title=Deregistration of Western Block Party|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#pact|publisher=Elections Canada}}</ref>\n* National Socialist ([[Martin K. Weiche]]), 1968\n* [[New Canada Party]] (Fred Reiner), 1968\n* [[Nationalist Party of Canada]] (Bob Smith), founded 1977\n* [[Christian Democrat Party of Canada]] (Sydney Thompson), 1981\n* [[Work Less Party]] (Betty Krawczyk), 2007\u20132010<ref name=\"Work Less Party Deregistered\">{{cite web|title=Deregistration of Western Block Party|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#wlp|publisher=Elections Canada}}</ref>\n* [[The Bridge Party of Canada]] (David Berlin), 2015\u20132017<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#bridge</ref>\n* [[Canada Party (2015)|Canada Party]] (II) (Jim Pankiw) 2015\u20132016<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#canpar</ref>\n* Seniors Party of Canada (Margaret Leigh Fairbairn), 2014-2016<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#senior</ref>\n\n== Unofficial designations and parties who never ran candidates ==\nThe following parties do not appear on the federal election archive.<ref>https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/ElectionsRidings/Elections</ref> They either did not run candidates in any election or ran candidates as independents.\n* [[Aboriginal Peoples Party of Canada]] (founded in 2005)\n* [[Absolutely Absurd Party]] (founded in 2003)\n* [[United Canadian Socialist Party]] (being launched in 2016)\n* [[Action Canada]] (founded in 1971)\n* [[Canadian Clean Start Party]] (founded in 2000)\n* [[Canadian Democratic Movement]] (founded in 2000)\n* [[Canadian Labour Party]], 1917-1929\n* [[Canadian Party for Renewal]], 1993\n* [[Canadian Union of Fascists]], 1930s\n* {{lang|fr|[[Candidat lib\u00e9ral des \u00e9lecteurs]]}}, 1962\u20131963\n* [[Christian Credit Party]], 1982-1983\n* [[Christian Freedom Party of Canada]], c. 1988-c. 1996 (an extension of the Social Credit Party)\n* [[Freedom Party of Canada]], founded 2001\n* Forward Canada Party, 1997\n* [[The Waffle|Movement for an Independent Socialist Canada]], 1974\n* [[National Alternative Party]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[National Party of Canada (1979)|National Party of Canada]] (I), 1979-1980s\n* [[New Capitalist Party]], 1965\n* [[James Sears|New Constitution Party of Canada]] (an unregistered party founded in 2015)\n* [[North American Labour Party]], 1970s\n* [[Parti national social chr\u00e9tien|National Unity Party]], 1938-1949\n* ''[[Parti Populaire des Putes]]'' (founded in 2000)\n* [[People's Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]] 1945\n* [[Ontario Party of Canada]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[Option Canada (political party)|Option Canada]] (founded in 1991)\n* [[Rest of Canada Party]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[Revolutionary Workers League (Canada)|Revolutionary Workers League]], 1977-1989\n* Revolutionary Workers Party, 1945-1953\n* Unity Party of Canada (founded in 2001)\n* [[Workers' Communist Party of Canada]], 1972-1980\n\n===Pre-confederation political parties===\n* [[Reform Party (pre-Confederation)|Reform Party]] (pre-Confederation)\n\n==Name changes==\n\n;Communist Party\nThe Communist Party of Canada changed its name multiple times in its history. It was founded as the Communist Party of Canada in 1921. From 1938 until 1943 its candidates ran under the banner Unity or United Progressive. In 1943 it adopted the name [[Labor-Progressive Party]]. It won one seat under this name in 1945. In 1959 it reverted to the name Communist Party of Canada and has kept that name to the present.\n\nThe Marxist\u2013Leninist Party of Canada unofficially uses the name \"Communist Party of Canada (Marxist\u2013Leninist)\", but Elections Canada does not allow it to be registered by that name because of potential confusion with the Communist Party of Canada.\n\n;Labour Party\nLabour Party candidates ran under numerous different designations:\n* Conservative-Labour (1872-1875)\n* Farmer Labour\n* Farmer-United Labour\n* Labour-Farmer\n* [[Liberal-Labour (Canada)|Liberal-Labour]] (1926-1968)\n* National Labour (1940)\n* United Farmers-Labour (1920)\n* United Farmers of Ontario-Labour (1919-1940)\n\n;Liberal Party\nDuring Robert Borden's coalition government of 1917-1920, the Liberal Party of Canada split into two groups: the [[Liberal\u2013Unionist]] who supported the coalition and the [[Laurier Liberals]] who opposed it.\n\n;Liberal-Progressive\nSome Liberal-Progressive candidates used the designations:\n*Liberal-Labour-Progressive or\n*National Liberal Progressive.\n\n;New Democratic Party\nThe Co-operative Commonwealth Federation used the name [[New Party (Canada)|New Party]] from 1958-1961 while it was transitioning to become the New Democratic Party. In French, the party used a literal translation of its name, ''F\u00e9d\u00e9ration du Commonwealth Coop\u00e9ratif'', from until 1955.\n\n;Progressive Conservative Party\nThe first Conservative Party used several different names during its existence:\n*[[Liberal-Conservative Party]] (some MPs until 1911),\n*[[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist Party]] (1917-1921),\n*[[National Liberal and Conservative Party]] (1920-1921),\n*National Government (1940),\n*[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative Party]] (1942-2003)\n\nThe second (and current) Conservative Party of Canada was a merger of the Canadian Alliance and the Progressive Conservative Party.\n\n;Progressive Party and United Farmers\nSome candidates for the Progressive Party of Canada used United Farmer designations:\n*[[Farmer (Party)|Farmer]] (1925 & 1930),\n*[[United Farmers of Canada]],\n*[[United Farmers of Alberta]], or\n*[[United Farmers of Ontario]].\n\n;Rhinoceros Party\nThe first Rhinoceros Party disbanded in 1993. When it was revived in 2006 it used the name \"neorhino.ca\". The party changed its name to Rhinoceros Party in 2010.\n\n;Social Credit Party and ''Ralliement cr\u00e9ditiste''\nSome ''Ralliement cr\u00e9ditiste'' used the name ''Ralliement des cr\u00e9ditistes'' from 1963 to 1967. One candidate used the designation ''Candidats des \u00e9lecteurs'' in 1957 and 1958. Others used the name Union des \u00e9lecteurs, although this was never formally registered.\n\nIn the 1940 election, 17 candidates ran jointly with the Social Credit Party under the name [[New Democracy (Canada)|New Democracy]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Politics}}\n*[[Federal political financing in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Elections in Canada}}\n{{Canadian federal political parties}}\n{{Lists of political parties in Canada}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Federal Political Parties In Canada}}\n[[Category:Canada politics-related lists|Political parties]]\n[[Category:Lists of political parties in Canada|*]]\n", "name_user": "Chad The Goatman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing a table error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_federal_political_parties_in_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Solomon Grundy (nursery rhyme)", "text_new": "{{short description|English nursery rhyme}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Salmagundi]] or [[Solomon Gundy]]}}\n[[File:BookOfNurseryRhymes p89.jpg|thumb|\"Here lies ye bodye of Solomon Grundy. Died on Saturday...\" An illustration from Clara E. Atwood's 1901 ''A Book of Nursery Rhymes'']]\n\n\"'''Solomon Grundy'''\" is an [[English people|English]] [[nursery rhyme]]. It has a [[Roud Folk Song Index]] number of 19299.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vwml.org/record/RoudFS/S276827 | title=Roud Folksong Index S276827Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday | publisher=[[English Folk Dance and Song Society]] | work=[[Vaughan Williams Memorial Library]] | accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe rhyme has varied very little since it was first collected by [[James Orchard Halliwell]] and published in 1842 with the lyrics:\n\n;Short version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy,\nBorn on a Monday,\nChristened on Tuesday,\nMarried on Wednesday,\nTook ill on Thursday,we are free\nGrew worse on Friday, \nDied on Saturday,\nBuried on Sunday,\nThat was the end,\nOf Solomon Grundy.<ref name=Opie1997>[[I. Opie and P. Opie]], ''The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes'' (Oxford University Press, 1951, 2nd edn., 1997), p. 394-5.</ref><ref>[http://www.rhymezone.com/r/gwic.cgi?Word=_&Path=goose/s/38// \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Rhyme Zone. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n;Long version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday, \nChristened on a stark and stormy Tuesday, \nMarried on a grey and grisly Wednesday, \nTook ill on a mild and mellow Thursday, \nGrew worse on a bright and breezy Friday, \nDied on a grey and glorious Saturday, \nBuried on a baking, blistering Sunday. \nThat was the end of Solomon Grundy.<ref>[http://www.nursery-rhymes.org/nursery-rhymes/solomon-grundy.html \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Mother Goose Nursery Rhymes.org. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The nursery rhyme is the inspiration for the [[DC Comics]] character [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Cyrus Gold/Solomon Grundy]], a large, strong [[zombie]] [[supervillain]] created in 1944 as an adversary for the [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]], though later a common foe of [[Batman]] and [[Superman]].<ref>Conroy, M. ''500 Comicbook Villains'' (Collins & Brown, 2004), p. 262.</ref>\n* In 1964, [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] singer [[Eric \"Monty\" Morris]] released the [[ska]] song \"[[Solomon Gundie]]\" whose lyrics were based on the nursery rhyme. It was [[cover version|covered]] in 1980 by French singer [[Amanda Lear]] to a chart success. \n* The premiere episode of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' (air date November 10, 1969) features a Solomon Grundy cartoon in which he washes only one part of the left half of his body each day. At the end of the week Solomon is still \"half dirty\".\n* Jamaican [[Deejay (Jamaican)|deejay]] [[Big Youth]] recorded the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on his 1972 album ''[[Screaming Target]]'', which was loosely based on the story of Solomon Grundy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Big-Youth-Screaming-Target/master/139872 |title=Big Youth - Screaming Target at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* \"Hippopotamus\" by Nokoinoko, a Japanese song, was based on the poem. It was aired on \"Hirake Ponkikki\", a TV show for kids, and became popular in 1970s. The strange lyrics made it a cult song and it was used in ''[[The Lost Village (anime)|The Lost Village]]'' anime in 2016.\n* In a 1979 episode of ''[[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]]'', \"Solomon / Grundy Binding\" is referenced on the box of ''ACME Jet-Propelled Skis''.\n* The poet [[Philippe Soupault]] adapted this rhyme and called it \"The Life of Philippe Soupault\".<ref>Stewart, Susan. ''Nonsense: Aspects of Intertextuality in Folklore and Literature'', Johns Hopkins, 1979, p. 191. {{ISBN|0-8018-2258-0}}</ref>\n* The comic book version of Solomon Grundy is mentioned in the song \"[[Superman's Song]]\" by the [[Crash Test Dummies]].\n* There was a professional wrestler named Solomon Grundy who competed as a \"hillbilly\" type character in bib overalls and competed primarily in the Dallas based Wild West and World Class Wrestling companies, as well as in Mexico for the CMLL promotion during the late 80's and early 1990s.\n* The 1992 song \"Mars Ultras, You'll Never Make the Station\" by the band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] refers to the song in the lines: \"Surrogate Grundy, sold on a Monday, to Richard and Judy\".\n* Comic artist and writer [[Kaori Yuki]] wrote a short story concerning the poem using characters from her series ''[[Earl Cain|Godchild]]'', which was published at the end of book five.<ref>[[Yuki, Kaori]]. ''Godchild'', vol 5, VIZ Media LLC, 2007.</ref> \n* The name and structure of [[Ian McDonald (author)|Ian McDonald]]'s [[science fiction]] novella \"The Days of Solomon Gursky\" (''[[Asimov's Science Fiction]]'' June 1998, reprinted in [[Mike Ashley (writer)|Mike Ashley]]'s 2006 anthology ''[[The Mammoth Book of Extreme Science Fiction]]'')<ref>{{isfdb title |82252|title=The Days of Solomon Gursky}}</ref> are based on the nursery rhyme. The title character (his name coincides with [[Mordecai Richler]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Solomon Gursky Was Here]]'') invents a way to resurrect the dead using [[nanotechnology]], developed in McDonald's 1994 novel ''Necroville''. The spin-off novella consists of seven episodical chapters (titled after the days of the week) showing in increasing intervals Gursky's life from the early 21st century through the [[posthuman]] future in space to the [[end of the universe]] when he constructs a [[Tipler machine]] to be reborn.\n* [[The Bluetones]] song \"[[Solomon Bites the Worm]]\" (1998) was based on this nursery rhyme.\n* Jamaican deejay [[Tapper Zukie]] released the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on the 2003 re-release of his 1973 album ''Man ah Warrior''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Tapper-Zukie-Man-Ah-Warrior/release/9125796 |title=Tapper Zukie - Man Ah Warrior (CD, Album) at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* Solomon Grundy appears as a character (and suspect) in [[Jasper Fforde]]'s novel ''[[The Big Over Easy]]'': \"'I'll be dead tired on Saturday,' he quipped to waiting journalists, 'but will bury myself in work again on Sunday.'\"<ref>Fforde, Jasper. ''The Big Over Easy'' (2006) p.163</ref>\n* \"Solomon Grundy\" is the title of the ninth track of ''[[Mic Tyson]]'', the third studio album of American rapper [[Sean Price]].\n* ''Solomon Grundy'', a feature film based on the poem and its structure, was released in 2012. Grundy is portrayed as a child's imaginary friend, and each of the poem's days is represented as a stage in the development of their relationship.<ref>{{IMDb title|1717686}}</ref>\n* The 2013 track \"Kingston Be Wise\" by [[Protoje]] from his album ''The 8 Year Affair'', references Solomon Grundy in the second verse: \"Then where the gun deh? Dead pon Saturday; Buried Sunday like Solomon Grundy.\"\n* In the 2016 movie ''[[The Accountant (2016 film)|The Accountant]]'', Ben Affleck's autistic character recites the rhyme \"Solomon Grundy\" to calm himself down.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* \"[[Monday's Child]]\", a traditional English rhyme mentioning the days of the week\n* \"[[Dashing Away with the Smoothing Iron]]\", a traditional [[English folk song]] written in the 19th century about a housewife carrying out one part of her linen chores each day of the week\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English nursery rhymes]]\n[[Category:Roud Folk Song Index songs]]\n[[Category:English folk songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about fictional male characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English nursery rhyme}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Salmagundi]] or [[Solomon Gundy]]}}\n[[File:BookOfNurseryRhymes p89.jpg|thumb|\"Here lies ye bodye of Solomon Grundy. Died on Saturday...\" An illustration from Clara E. Atwood's 1901 ''A Book of Nursery Rhymes'']]\n\n\"'''Solomon Grundy'''\" is an [[English people|English]] [[nursery rhyme]]. It has a [[Roud Folk Song Index]] number of 19299.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vwml.org/record/RoudFS/S276827 | title=Roud Folksong Index S276827Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday | publisher=[[English Folk Dance and Song Society]] | work=[[Vaughan Williams Memorial Library]] | accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe rhyme has varied very little since it was first collected by [[James Orchard Halliwell]] and published in 1842 with the lyrics:\n\n;Short version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy,\nBorn on a Monday,\nChristened on Tuesday,\nMarried on Wednesday,\nTook ill on Thursday,\nGrew worse on Friday, \nDied on Saturday,\nBuried on Sunday,\nThat was the end,\nOf Solomon Grundy.<ref name=Opie1997>[[I. Opie and P. Opie]], ''The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes'' (Oxford University Press, 1951, 2nd edn., 1997), p. 394-5.</ref><ref>[http://www.rhymezone.com/r/gwic.cgi?Word=_&Path=goose/s/38// \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Rhyme Zone. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n;Long version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday, \nChristened on a stark and stormy Tuesday, \nMarried on a grey and grisly Wednesday, \nTook ill on a mild and mellow Thursday, \nGrew worse on a bright and breezy Friday, \nDied on a grey and glorious Saturday, \nBuried on a baking, blistering Sunday. \nThat was the end of Solomon Grundy.<ref>[http://www.nursery-rhymes.org/nursery-rhymes/solomon-grundy.html \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Mother Goose Nursery Rhymes.org. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The nursery rhyme is the inspiration for the [[DC Comics]] character [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Cyrus Gold/Solomon Grundy]], a large, strong [[zombie]] [[supervillain]] created in 1944 as an adversary for the [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]], though later a common foe of [[Batman]] and [[Superman]].<ref>Conroy, M. ''500 Comicbook Villains'' (Collins & Brown, 2004), p. 262.</ref>\n* In 1964, [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] singer [[Eric \"Monty\" Morris]] released the [[ska]] song \"[[Solomon Gundie]]\" whose lyrics were based on the nursery rhyme. It was [[cover version|covered]] in 1980 by French singer [[Amanda Lear]] to a chart success. \n* The premiere episode of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' (air date November 10, 1969) features a Solomon Grundy cartoon in which he washes only one part of the left half of his body each day. At the end of the week Solomon is still \"half dirty\".\n* Jamaican [[Deejay (Jamaican)|deejay]] [[Big Youth]] recorded the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on his 1972 album ''[[Screaming Target]]'', which was loosely based on the story of Solomon Grundy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Big-Youth-Screaming-Target/master/139872 |title=Big Youth - Screaming Target at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* \"Hippopotamus\" by Nokoinoko, a Japanese song, was based on the poem. It was aired on \"Hirake Ponkikki\", a TV show for kids, and became popular in 1970s. The strange lyrics made it a cult song and it was used in ''[[The Lost Village (anime)|The Lost Village]]'' anime in 2016.\n* In a 1979 episode of ''[[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]]'', \"Solomon / Grundy Binding\" is referenced on the box of ''ACME Jet-Propelled Skis''.\n* The poet [[Philippe Soupault]] adapted this rhyme and called it \"The Life of Philippe Soupault\".<ref>Stewart, Susan. ''Nonsense: Aspects of Intertextuality in Folklore and Literature'', Johns Hopkins, 1979, p. 191. {{ISBN|0-8018-2258-0}}</ref>\n* The comic book version of Solomon Grundy is mentioned in the song \"[[Superman's Song]]\" by the [[Crash Test Dummies]].\n* There was a professional wrestler named Solomon Grundy who competed as a \"hillbilly\" type character in bib overalls and competed primarily in the Dallas based Wild West and World Class Wrestling companies, as well as in Mexico for the CMLL promotion during the late 80's and early 1990s.\n* The 1992 song \"Mars Ultras, You'll Never Make the Station\" by the band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] refers to the song in the lines: \"Surrogate Grundy, sold on a Monday, to Richard and Judy\".\n* Comic artist and writer [[Kaori Yuki]] wrote a short story concerning the poem using characters from her series ''[[Earl Cain|Godchild]]'', which was published at the end of book five.<ref>[[Yuki, Kaori]]. ''Godchild'', vol 5, VIZ Media LLC, 2007.</ref> \n* The name and structure of [[Ian McDonald (author)|Ian McDonald]]'s [[science fiction]] novella \"The Days of Solomon Gursky\" (''[[Asimov's Science Fiction]]'' June 1998, reprinted in [[Mike Ashley (writer)|Mike Ashley]]'s 2006 anthology ''[[The Mammoth Book of Extreme Science Fiction]]'')<ref>{{isfdb title |82252|title=The Days of Solomon Gursky}}</ref> are based on the nursery rhyme. The title character (his name coincides with [[Mordecai Richler]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Solomon Gursky Was Here]]'') invents a way to resurrect the dead using [[nanotechnology]], developed in McDonald's 1994 novel ''Necroville''. The spin-off novella consists of seven episodical chapters (titled after the days of the week) showing in increasing intervals Gursky's life from the early 21st century through the [[posthuman]] future in space to the [[end of the universe]] when he constructs a [[Tipler machine]] to be reborn.\n* [[The Bluetones]] song \"[[Solomon Bites the Worm]]\" (1998) was based on this nursery rhyme.\n* Jamaican deejay [[Tapper Zukie]] released the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on the 2003 re-release of his 1973 album ''Man ah Warrior''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Tapper-Zukie-Man-Ah-Warrior/release/9125796 |title=Tapper Zukie - Man Ah Warrior (CD, Album) at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* Solomon Grundy appears as a character (and suspect) in [[Jasper Fforde]]'s novel ''[[The Big Over Easy]]'': \"'I'll be dead tired on Saturday,' he quipped to waiting journalists, 'but will bury myself in work again on Sunday.'\"<ref>Fforde, Jasper. ''The Big Over Easy'' (2006) p.163</ref>\n* \"Solomon Grundy\" is the title of the ninth track of ''[[Mic Tyson]]'', the third studio album of American rapper [[Sean Price]].\n* ''Solomon Grundy'', a feature film based on the poem and its structure, was released in 2012. Grundy is portrayed as a child's imaginary friend, and each of the poem's days is represented as a stage in the development of their relationship.<ref>{{IMDb title|1717686}}</ref>\n* The 2013 track \"Kingston Be Wise\" by [[Protoje]] from his album ''The 8 Year Affair'', references Solomon Grundy in the second verse: \"Then where the gun deh? Dead pon Saturday; Buried Sunday like Solomon Grundy.\"\n* In the 2016 movie ''[[The Accountant (2016 film)|The Accountant]]'', Ben Affleck's autistic character recites the rhyme \"Solomon Grundy\" to calm himself down.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* \"[[Monday's Child]]\", a traditional English rhyme mentioning the days of the week\n* \"[[Dashing Away with the Smoothing Iron]]\", a traditional [[English folk song]] written in the 19th century about a housewife carrying out one part of her linen chores each day of the week\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English nursery rhymes]]\n[[Category:Roud Folk Song Index songs]]\n[[Category:English folk songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about fictional male characters]]\n", "name_user": "59.102.64.240", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLyrics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_Grundy_(nursery_rhyme)"}
{"title_page": "Hilda Koronel", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino actress}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox person\n| name                    = Hilda Koronel\n| image                   = \n| caption                 = \n| birth_name               = Susan Reid\n| birth_date               = {{Birth date and age|1957|01|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Angeles City]], [[Pampanga]], [[Philippines]]\n| death_date               = \n| death_place              = \n| occupation              = \n| yearsactive             = 1970\u2013present\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|[[Jay Ilagan]]|1980|1992|end={{abbr|div.|divorced}}}} <br> {{marriage|Ralph Moore Jr.|2000}}\n| children                = 5\n}}\n\n'''Hilda Koronel''' (born '''Susan Reid'''; January 17, 1957) is a [[Metro Manila Film Festival|MMFF]], [[FAMAS Award|FAMAS]], [[Film Academy of the Philippines|Luna]] and [[Gawad Urian Award|Urian]] award-winning [[Philippines|Filipino]] [[actress]]. Born to a Filipino mother and an [[United States|American]] father who was a serviceman in [[Clark Air Base]], she has starred in around 45 films, many of which are critically acclaimed, since 1970.\n\nShe started her showbiz career in the early 70s as a Lea Productions' contract star and was paired with Ed Finlan, Walter Navarro, Tirso Cruz, III and Jay Ilagan which eventually became her husband. Because of her natural gift of acting, Lino Brocka took notice of her and directed her in a weekly drama show, entitled, \"Hilda\". Her career got off to an unprecedented start becoming the youngest winner of the [[FAMAS Award|FAMAS]] Best Supporting Actress award in 1970 right at the beginning of her career which she won at the age of just 13 for her role in the 1970 film ''Santiago''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entertainment.inquirer.net/356863/hilda-koronel-%e2%80%8d%e2%80%8d%e2%80%8don-her-50th-year-%e2%80%8din-show-biz|title=Hilda Koronel \u200d\u200d\u200don her 50th year \u200din show biz|last=Cruz|first=Marinel R.|website=entertainment.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975 and 1976, she starred in the [[Lino Brocka]] classics ''[[Maynila: Sa mga Kuko ng Liwanag]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emirates247.com/entertainment/filipino-classic-with-hilda-korone-makes-a-splash-at-cannes-2013-05-23-1.507547|title=Hilda Korone makes a splash at Cannes|last=|first=|date=|website=Emirates 24/7|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, which won six FAMAS awards in [[1976 in film|1976]], and ''[[Insiang]]'', which won both a [[FAMAS Award]] and a [[Gawad Urian Award]] in 1977. To date she has won three awards and received 11 nominations.\n\nIn 2013, she received a [[Film Academy of the Philippines|Luna Award]] for best supporting actress for her role in ''[[The Mistress (2012 film)|The Mistress]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/philippines/philippine-daily-inquirer-1109/20130509/282432756665666|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/05/09/13/mistress-leads-luna-nominations-near-sweep|title='Mistress' leads Luna nominations with near-sweep|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe attended Manila Central University (MCU) for her secondary education and finished International Studies at Maryknoll College, now Miriam College.\n\nIn May 2000, Koronel married [[Filipino-American]] businessman Ralph Moore, Jr. in [[Laughlin, Nevada]].\n\nKoronel has 5 children. Leona and Ivy (with the late-actor Jay Ilagan); Isabel (with the late Bambi del Castillo); Gaby (with Spanky Monserrat); and Diego (with Dr. Victor Lopez).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Network\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1997 || ''[[Esperanza (Philippine TV series)|Esperanza]]'' || Stella || rowspan=\"5\"|[[ABS-CBN]]\n|-\n| ''[[Mula Sa Puso]]'' || Jerry\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1998 || ''[[Ang Munting Paraiso]]'' || Cindy\n|-\n| ''[[Sa Sandaling Kailangan Mo Ako]]'' || (Mother)\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Sa Dulo Ng Walang Hanggan]]'' || Dolores\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Kung Mawawala Ka]]'' || Alicia || [[GMA Network]]\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Ikaw Ang Lahat Sa Akin]]'' || Susanna Ynares || [[ABS-CBN]]\n|}\n\n===Movies===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Production Company\n|-\n| 1970 || ''[[Santiago! (film)]]'' || Cristina || Lea Productions\n|-\n| 1974 || ''[[Tinimbang Ka Ngunit Kulang]]'' || Evangeline Ortega || Cinemanila Corporation\n|-\n| 1975 || ''[[Maynila sa mga Kuko ng Liwanag]]'' || Ligaya Paraiso || Cinemanila Corporation\n|-\n| 1976 || ''[[Insiang]]'' || Insiang|| Cinemanila Corporation\n|-\n| 1977 || ''[[Kung Mangarap Ka't Magising]]'' || Anna || [[LVN Pictures]]\n|-\n| 1978 || ''[[Hayop sa Hayop]]'' || Alice || [[Showbiz Associates Inc.]]\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Evening Class]]'' ||  || [[Cinex Films  ]]\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Kasal (1979 film)|Kasal]]'' || Grace || [[Trigon Cinema]]\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Nakaw na Pag-ibig]]'' ||Cynthia Ocampo || [[Associated Entertainment]]\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[PX (film)|PX]]'' ||Lydia|| [[Trigon Cinema]]\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Gaano Kadalas ang Minsan?]]'' || Elsa || [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Sana Bukas pa ang Kahapon]]'' || Ana || [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1983 || ''[[Palabra de Honor]]'' ||  || [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Kung Mahawi man ang Ulap]]'' ||  || [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[Working Girls (1984 film)|Working Girls]]'' || Carla Asuncion || [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[Beloved (1985 film)|Beloved]]'' ||Renee|| [[Viva Films]]\n|-\n| 1986 || ''Nasaan Ka Nang Kailangan Kita''  || Jenny || [[Regal Entertainment|Regal Films]]\n|-\n| 1989 || ''Babangon Ako't Dudurugin Kita''  || Via || [[Viva Films|VIVA Films]]\n|-\n| 1990 || ''Nagsimula sa Puso'' || Celine || [[Vision Exponents]]\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Tanging Yaman'' || Celine || rowspan=\"3\"|[[Star Cinema]]\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Santa Santita'' ||\n|-\n| 2005 || ''Nasaan Ka Man'' || Trining\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Eternity'' || Chayong || [[Regal Entertainment|Regal Films]]\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Villa Estrella'' || Jeline || rowspan=\"3\"|[[Star Cinema]]\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Way Back Home'' || Jomar Carey\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[The Mistress (2012 film)|The Mistress]]'' || Regina Torres\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n\n===FAMAS (Filipino Academy of Movie Arts and Sciences Awards)===\n\n{| width=\"70%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year\n! width=\"35%\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"40%\"| Category\n! width=\"15%\"| Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[61st FAMAS Awards|2013]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[The Mistress (2012 film)|The Mistress]]''\n| align=\"center\" rowspan = 4| [[FAMAS Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2006\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Nasaan Ka Man]]'' \n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2004\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Crying Ladies]]'' \n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 1990\n| align=\"center\"| Babangon ako't Dudurugin Kita\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[31st FAMAS Awards|1983]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''PX''\n| align=\"center\" rowspan = 3| [[FAMAS Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[25th FAMAS Awards|1977]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Insiang]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[24th FAMAS Awards|1976]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[The Claws of Light|Maynila sa Kuko ng Liwanag]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[19th FAMAS Awards|1971]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''Santiago''\n| align=\"center\" | [[FAMAS Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n===[[Film Academy of the Philippines]] (Luna Awards)===\n\n{| width=\"70%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year\n! width=\"35%\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"40%\"| Category\n! width=\"15%\"| Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2013\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[The Mistress (2012 film)|The Mistress]]''\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=3| Best Supporting Actress\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2006\n| align=\"center\"|  ''[[Nasaan Ka Man]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2005\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Santa Santita]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===[[Gawad Urian for Best Actress|Gawad Urian (Manunuri ng Pelikulang Pilipino)]]===\n\n{| width=\"70%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year\n! width=\"35%\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"40%\"| Category\n! width=\"15%\"| Result\n|-\n|  align=\"center\"| 2006\n| align=\"center\"|  ''[[Santa Santita]]''\n| rowspan = 3 align=\"center\"| ''Best Supporting Actress'''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|  align=\"center\"| 2004\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Crying Ladies]]'' \n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2001\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Tanging Yaman]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2nd Gawad Urian Awards|1978]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''Kung Mangrap Ka't Magising''\n| rowspan = 2 align=\"center\"| ''Best Actress''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[1st Gawad Urian Awards|1977]]\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Insiang]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n===Maria Clara Awards===\n{| width=\"70%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year\n! width=\"35%\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"40%\"| Category\n! width=\"15%\"| Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|2006\n| align=\"center\"| ''[[Nasaan Ka Man]]''\n| align=\"center\" | Best Supporting Actress\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Awards from the Press===\n\n{| width=\"70%\" class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | '''Star Awards for Movies (Philippine Movie Press Club)'''\n|-\n! width=\"10%\"| Year\n! width=\"35%\"| Nominated work\n! width=\"40%\"| Category\n! width=\"15%\"| Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2013\n| align=\"center\"|  ''[[The Mistress (2012 film)|The Mistress]]''\n| align=