{"title_page": "Rastriya Janata Party Nepal", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Rastriya Janata Party Nepal\n| logo = RJPN.jpg\n| colorcode = #FFb300\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2017|04|20|df=y}}\n| ideology = [[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<br />[[Social democracy]]<br />[[Madhesi people|Madhesi]] rights<br />[[Newar people|Janajati]] rights<br />[[Secularism]]\n| headquarters = \n| international = \n| website = \n| country = Nepal\n| position = [[Centre-left]]\n| native_name = \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u091c\u0928\u0924\u093e \u092a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091f\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\n| flag = \n| abbreviation = RJPN\n| merger = [[Terai-Madhesh Loktantrik Party|Terai Madhes Loktantrik Party]] <br /> [[Sadbhavana Party]] <br /> Rastriya Madhes Samajwadi Party <br /> [[Terai Madhes Sadbhavana Party|Tarai Madhes Sadbhawana Party]] <br /> Madhesi Jana Adhikar Forum (Republican) <br /> [[Nepal Sadbhawana Party]]\n| chairperson = [[Anil Kumar Jha]]<br />(Rotation basis)\n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| seats1_title = Seats in [[Pratinidhi Sabha]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|17|275|hex=#FFb300}}\n| seats2_title = Seats in [[Rastriya Sabha]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|2|59|hex=#FFb300}}\n| symbol = [[File:Rastriya Janata Party.png|100px]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Rastriya Janata Party, Nepal''', abbr. ''RJPN'' ({{lang-ne|\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u091c\u0928\u0924\u093e \u092a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091f\u0940, \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932}},  [[translation]]: '''National People's Party, Nepal''') is the fourth-largest [[List of political parties in Nepal|political party in Nepal]] after the [[Nepali Congress]], the [[Nepal Communist Party]] and the [[Samajbadi Party, Nepal]]. It was formed on 21 April 2017 after the merger of [[Tarai Madhes Loktantrik Party]], led by the [[Mahantha Thakur]], [[Sadbhavana Party]], led by the [[Rajendra Mahato]], [[Nepal Sadbhawana Party]], led by the [[Anil Kumar Jha]], [[Terai Madhes Sadbhavana Party|Terai Madhes Sadbhawana Party]], led by the Mahendra Yadav, Madhesi Jana Adhikar Forum (Republican), led by Rajkishor Yadav and Rastriya Madhesh Samajwadi Party, led by [[Sarad Singh Bhandari]]. The party was founded with the ideology of [[democratic system]]\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Post Report |url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-04-20/five-madhes-based-parties-unite-to-form-rastriya-janata-party.html |title=Six Madhes-based parties unite to form Rastriya Janata Party (Update)|website=Ekantipur |date=2014-12-01 |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/five-madhesi-parties-unify-form-rastriya-janata-party/ |title=Five Madhesi parties unify to form Rastriya Janata Party |website=THT Online |date= |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/18554/ |title=Glimpses of Rastriya Janata Party at birth |website=Nagarik News |date= |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com.np/news/2017-04-21/six-madhes-based-parties-under-one-umbrella.html</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\n*Chairman [[Mahantha Thakur]]\n*Chairman [[Rajendra Mahato]]\n*Chairman [[Anil Kumar Jha]]\n*Chairman  Mahendra Yadav\n*Chairman  Rajkishor Yadav\n*Chairman [[Sarad Singh Bhandari]]\n*General Secretary [[Rajeev Jha]] <ref>https://madheshvani.com/en/detail/3596/rajeev-jha</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\nOn 14 April 2017, six of the seven constituents of the Unified Democratic Madhesi Front agreed in principle to merge in a bid to form a strong force representing the [[Terai]] region.<ref>{{cite web|title=UDMF parties agree in principle to merge|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/18124/|website=Nagarik News|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref> The party was formed on 21 April, as the Rastriya Janata Party and Mahanta Thakur was announced as its chairperson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six UDMF constituents merge|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/six-united-democratic-madhesi-front-constituents-merge/|website=THT Online|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref> The party on 26 April, changed its name to Rastriya Janata Party Nepal after it clashed with another party bearing the name Rastriya Janata Party, which later merged with [[Nepal Loktantrik Forum]], registered in the Election Commission.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newly formed RJP to change party name to avoid clash|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-04-26/newly-formed-rjp-to-change-party-name-to-avoid-clash.html|website=Ekantipur|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe party registered at the [[Election Commission, Nepal|Election Commission]] on 7 July 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-07-07/rjp-n-all-set-to-register-at-ec-today.html|title=RJP-N registered at EC today|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/2017/07/07/403129|title=RJPN finally files registration application at Election Commission \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Elections ===\nThe party had initially decided to not participate in the third phase of the local elections but changed their decision later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kathmandutribune.com/rastriya-janata-party-nepal-undecided-participating-province-2-election/|title=Rastriya Janata Party Nepal undecided on participating in Province 2 election|access-date=2017-09-05|language=en|website=Kathmandu Tribune}}</ref> The party had the second highest candidates elected in [[Province No. 2]] with 1,112 candidates being elected. The party won 25 mayoral posts, including a win in [[Janakpur, Nepal|Janakpur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-09-24/rjpns-raj-kishor-sah-elected-mayor-of-janakpur-sub-metro.html|title=RJPN\u2019s Raj Kishor Sah elected mayor of Janakpur Sub-Metro|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2017 Nepalese legislative election|legislative and]] [[2017 Nepalese provincial elections|provincial elections]], RJPN formed an alliance with [[Upendra Yadav]] led [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/29894/|title=FSFN, RJPN sign poll alliance deal in Province 2|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The party won 17 seats in the [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]] and finished with the fourth highest vote count in [[proportional representation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/32740/?categoryId=81|title=PR vote counting concludes|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The party won in key areas of their home province in [[Province No. 2]], including senior leader [[Rajendra Mahato]] defeating [[Ministry of Defence (Nepal)|defence minister]] [[Bimalendra Nidhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mahato-defeats-nidhi-dhanusa-1/|title=Mahato defeats Nidhi in Dhanusa 1|date=2017-12-10|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref> The party was also one of five parties to be declared \"national parties\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://peoplesreview.com.np/2017/12/20/only-five-parties-crossed-the-threshold-margin-in-pr-votes/|title=Only five parties crossed the threshold margin in PR votes - People's Review|work=People's Review|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 25 seats in the [[Pradesh Sabha|provincial assembly]] for [[Province No. 2]], 1 seat in [[Province No. 5]] and 2 seats in [[Sudurpashchim Pradesh|Sudurpashchim]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-12-23/ec-allots-proportional-seats-of-provincial-vote.html|title=EC allots proportional seats of provincial vote|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/33048/?categoryId=81|title=UML, NC and Maoists win 75, 72 and 35 provincial assembly PR seats|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en}}</ref> Following the election, RJPN and [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal|Federal Socialist Forum]] announced that they would form a coalition government in [[Province No. 2]], with [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal|FSFN]] getting the post of Chief Minister and RJPN getting the post of Speaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fsf-n-rjp-n-agree-form-coalition-government-province-2/|title=FSF-N and RJP-N agree to form coalition government in Province 2|date=2018-02-06|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/36063/|title=Province 2: Chief Minister to FSFN, Speaker to RJPN|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 2 seats in the [[National Assembly (Nepal)|National Assembly]] elections, both candidates were elected unopposed from [[Province No. 2]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-02/20/c_136987107.htm|title=Nepal's National Assembly gets full shape - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-dozen-national-assembly-members-elected-unopposed/|title=Two dozen NA members elected unopposed|date=2018-01-30|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref> On 20 April 2018, disgruntled leaders led by Ashok Kumar Yadav broke away from the party and formed Rastriya Janata Party (Democratic).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-04-20/disgruntled-leaders-of-rjpn-forms-new.html|title=Disgruntled RJPN leaders form new party|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Election\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Leader\n! colspan=\"2\" |Votes\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Position\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Resulting government\n|-\n!#\n!%\n\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2017 Nepalese legislative election|2017]]\n|[[Mahanth Thakur]]\n|472,254\n|4.95\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Infobox political party/seats|17|275|#FFb300}}\n|4th\n|{{no2|[[CPN (UML)]]-[[CPN (Maoist Centre)]]}}\n|}\n\n== Presence in various provinces ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Province\n!Seats\n!Year of election\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Province No. 2|Province No. 2]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|25|107|#FFb300}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[2017 Nepalese provincial elections|2017]]\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Province No. 5|Province No. 5]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|1|87|#FFb300}}\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Sudurpashchim|Sudurpashchim]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|2|53|#FFb300}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Political parties in Nepal}}\n[[Category:Rastriya Janata Party Nepal| ]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Rastriya Janata Party Nepal\n| logo = RJPN.jpg\n| colorcode = #FFb300\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2017|04|20|df=y}}\n| ideology = [[Regionalism (politics)|Regionalism]]<br />[[Social democracy]]<br />[[Madhesi people|Madhesi]] rights<br />[[Newar people|Janajati]] rights<br />[[Secularism]]\n| headquarters = \n| international = \n| website = \n| country = Nepal\n| position = [[Centre-left]]\n| native_name = \u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u091c\u0928\u0924\u093e \u092a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091f\u0940 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\n| flag = \n| abbreviation = RJPN\n| merger = [[Terai-Madhesh Loktantrik Party|Terai Madhes Loktantrik Party]] <br /> [[Sadbhavana Party]] <br /> Rastriya Madhes Samajwadi Party <br /> [[Terai Madhes Sadbhavana Party|Tarai Madhes Sadbhawana Party]] <br /> Madhesi Jana Adhikar Forum (Republican) <br /> [[Nepal Sadbhawana Party]]\n| chairperson = [[Anil Kumar Jha]]<br />(Rotation basis)\n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| seats1_title = Seats in [[Pratinidhi Sabha]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|17|275|hex=#FFb300}}\n| seats2_title = Seats in [[Rastriya Sabha]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|2|59|hex=#FFb300}}\n| symbol = [[File:Rastriya Janata Party.png|100px]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Rastriya Janata Party, Nepal''', abbr. ''RJPN'' ({{lang-ne|\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f \u091c\u0928\u0924\u093e \u092a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091f\u0940, \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932}},  [[translation]]: '''National People's Party, Nepal''') is the fourth-largest [[List of political parties in Nepal|political party in Nepal]] after the [[Nepali Congress]], the [[Nepal Communist Party]] and the [[Samajbadi Party, Nepal]]. It was formed on 21 April 2017 after the merger of [[Tarai Madhes Loktantrik Party]], led by the [[Mahantha Thakur]], [[Sadbhavana Party]], led by the [[Rajendra Mahato]], [[Nepal Sadbhawana Party]], led by the [[Anil Kumar Jha]], [[Terai Madhes Sadbhavana Party|Terai Madhes Sadbhawana Party]], led by the Mahendra Yadav, Madhesi Jana Adhikar Forum (Republican), led by Rajkishor Yadav and Rastriya Madhesh Samajwadi Party, led by [[Sarad Singh Bhandari]]. The party was founded with the ideology of [[democratic system]]\n<ref>{{cite web|author=Post Report |url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-04-20/five-madhes-based-parties-unite-to-form-rastriya-janata-party.html |title=Six Madhes-based parties unite to form Rastriya Janata Party (Update)|website=Ekantipur |date=2014-12-01 |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/five-madhesi-parties-unify-form-rastriya-janata-party/ |title=Five Madhesi parties unify to form Rastriya Janata Party |website=THT Online |date= |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/18554/ |title=Glimpses of Rastriya Janata Party at birth |website=Nagarik News |date= |accessdate=2017-04-21}}</ref><ref>http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com.np/news/2017-04-21/six-madhes-based-parties-under-one-umbrella.html</ref>\n\n\n\n== Leadership ==\n*Chairman [[ Mahantha Thakur]]\n*Chairman [[Rajendra Mahato]]\n*Chairman [[ Anil Kumar Jha]]\n*Chairman  Mahendra Yadav\n*Chairman  Rajkishor Yadav\n*Chairman [[Sarad Singh Bhandari]]\n\n*General Secretary [[Rajeev Jha]] <ref>https://madheshvani.com/en/detail/3596/rajeev-jha</ref>\n\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\nOn 14 April 2017, six of the seven constituents of the Unified Democratic Madhesi Front agreed in principle to merge in a bid to form a strong force representing the [[Terai]] region.<ref>{{cite web|title=UDMF parties agree in principle to merge|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/18124/|website=Nagarik News|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref> The party was formed on 21 April, as the Rastriya Janata Party and Mahanta Thakur was announced as its chairperson.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six UDMF constituents merge|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/six-united-democratic-madhesi-front-constituents-merge/|website=THT Online|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref> The party on 26 April, changed its name to Rastriya Janata Party Nepal after it clashed with another party bearing the name Rastriya Janata Party, which later merged with [[Nepal Loktantrik Forum]], registered in the Election Commission.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newly formed RJP to change party name to avoid clash|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-04-26/newly-formed-rjp-to-change-party-name-to-avoid-clash.html|website=Ekantipur|access-date=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe party registered at the [[Election Commission, Nepal|Election Commission]] on 7 July 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-07-07/rjp-n-all-set-to-register-at-ec-today.html|title=RJP-N registered at EC today|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/2017/07/07/403129|title=RJPN finally files registration application at Election Commission \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Elections ===\nThe party had initially decided to not participate in the third phase of the local elections but changed their decision later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kathmandutribune.com/rastriya-janata-party-nepal-undecided-participating-province-2-election/|title=Rastriya Janata Party Nepal undecided on participating in Province 2 election|access-date=2017-09-05|language=en|website=Kathmandu Tribune}}</ref> The party had the second highest candidates elected in [[Province No. 2]] with 1,112 candidates being elected. The party won 25 mayoral posts, including a win in [[Janakpur, Nepal|Janakpur]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-09-24/rjpns-raj-kishor-sah-elected-mayor-of-janakpur-sub-metro.html|title=RJPN\u2019s Raj Kishor Sah elected mayor of Janakpur Sub-Metro|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2017 Nepalese legislative election|legislative and]] [[2017 Nepalese provincial elections|provincial elections]], RJPN formed an alliance with [[Upendra Yadav]] led [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/29894/|title=FSFN, RJPN sign poll alliance deal in Province 2|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The party won 17 seats in the [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]] and finished with the fourth highest vote count in [[proportional representation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/32740/?categoryId=81|title=PR vote counting concludes|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> The party won in key areas of their home province in [[Province No. 2]], including senior leader [[Rajendra Mahato]] defeating [[Ministry of Defence (Nepal)|defence minister]] [[Bimalendra Nidhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mahato-defeats-nidhi-dhanusa-1/|title=Mahato defeats Nidhi in Dhanusa 1|date=2017-12-10|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref> The party was also one of five parties to be declared \"national parties\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://peoplesreview.com.np/2017/12/20/only-five-parties-crossed-the-threshold-margin-in-pr-votes/|title=Only five parties crossed the threshold margin in PR votes - People's Review|work=People's Review|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 25 seats in the [[Pradesh Sabha|provincial assembly]] for [[Province No. 2]], 1 seat in [[Province No. 5]] and 2 seats in [[Sudurpashchim Pradesh|Sudurpashchim]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2017-12-23/ec-allots-proportional-seats-of-provincial-vote.html|title=EC allots proportional seats of provincial vote|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/33048/?categoryId=81|title=UML, NC and Maoists win 75, 72 and 35 provincial assembly PR seats|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en}}</ref> Following the election, RJPN and [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal|Federal Socialist Forum]] announced that they would form a coalition government in [[Province No. 2]], with [[Federal Socialist Forum, Nepal|FSFN]] getting the post of Chief Minister and RJPN getting the post of Speaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/fsf-n-rjp-n-agree-form-coalition-government-province-2/|title=FSF-N and RJP-N agree to form coalition government in Province 2|date=2018-02-06|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/36063/|title=Province 2: Chief Minister to FSFN, Speaker to RJPN|work=My Republica|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe party won 2 seats in the [[National Assembly (Nepal)|National Assembly]] elections, both candidates were elected unopposed from [[Province No. 2]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-02/20/c_136987107.htm|title=Nepal's National Assembly gets full shape - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/two-dozen-national-assembly-members-elected-unopposed/|title=Two dozen NA members elected unopposed|date=2018-01-30|work=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref> On 20 April 2018, disgruntled leaders led by Ashok Kumar Yadav broke away from the party and formed Rastriya Janata Party (Democratic).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-04-20/disgruntled-leaders-of-rjpn-forms-new.html|title=Disgruntled RJPN leaders form new party|access-date=2018-04-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Election\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Leader\n! colspan=\"2\" |Votes\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Seats\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Position\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Resulting government\n|-\n!#\n!%\n\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2017 Nepalese legislative election|2017]]\n|[[Mahanth Thakur]]\n|472,254\n|4.95\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{Infobox political party/seats|17|275|#FFb300}}\n|4th\n|{{no2|[[CPN (UML)]]-[[CPN (Maoist Centre)]]}}\n|}\n\n== Presence in various provinces ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Province\n!Seats\n!Year of election\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Province No. 2|Province No. 2]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|25|107|#FFb300}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[2017 Nepalese provincial elections|2017]]\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Province No. 5|Province No. 5]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|1|87|#FFb300}}\n|-\n|[[Provincial Assembly of Sudurpashchim|Sudurpashchim]]\n|{{Infobox political party/seats|2|53|#FFb300}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Political parties in Nepal}}\n[[Category:Rastriya Janata Party Nepal| ]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "Xbony2", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed extra spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rastriya_Janata_Party_Nepal"}
